Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Hi Julien - several comments:
- Could you add the bug number to the description?
- Did you check that this behavior only happens on update()?

Thanks for working on this

Patch Set 1:

Also, don't you want to six.text_type(e)?

Patch Set 1:

Hi Arnaud,

I didn't open any bug, I'm just fixing the issue right away. I can open a bug if you really think it's worth it, even if I don't. :)

I only had this problem on update, but looking at the rest of the code I think it could happen anywhere. I think it would be even better to log the error from the function calling update(), but I'm not sure which one it is. Hint?

Patch Set 1:

Julien - I want to make sure the logging is consistent across registry api calls.
I think this is this OK to log here since it would be complicated to have a specific message in the upper layer.
I would be interested to have other point of views on this.

Thank you

Patch Set 1:

For logging code position, I think Arnaud Legendre's suggestion is reasonable.

But I'm a little worried that whether this patch should be used to cover other functions, like create() since from the commit message seems we are fixing the issue for update() only.

So IMO it will be cool if we have a more complete bug report/description to make sure if we should handle those all interfaces by this patch. And from the exception stack, you could provide it in the bug report, we could know which function calling update() within upper layer code also.
